    "106716460"
  ],
  "bib_entries": {
    "106716460": {
      "title": "Diffuse Scattering and Defect Structure Simulations: A Cook Book Using the Program DISCUS",
      "abstract": "In recent years, it has become apparent that knowing the average atomic structure of materials is insufficient to understand their properties. Diffuse scattering in addition to the Bragg scattering holds the key to learning about defects in materials, the topic of many recent books. What has been missing is a detailed step-by-step guide on how to simulate disordered materials. The DISCUS cook book fills this need covering simple topics such as building a computer crystal to complex topics such as domain structures, stacking faults or using advanced refinement techniques to adjust parameters on a disordered model. The book contains a CDROM with all files needed to recreate every example given using the program DISCUS. The reader is free to follow the principles behind simulating disordered materials or to get down into the details and run or modify the given examples."
    },
    "135602296": {
      "title": "Local Structure from Diffraction",
      "abstract": "PDF Analysis Applied to Crystalline Materials T. Egami. Anomalous X-Ray Scattering from Disordered Materials D.L. Price, M.-L. Saboungi. The Recording and Interpretation of Diffuse X-Ray Scattering T.R. Welberry. Recent Advances in Structure Refinement for Liquids and Disordered Materials A.K. Soper. Neutron Scattering and Monte Carlo Studies of Disorder in Oxides and Hydrides W. Schweika, M. Pionke. Reverse Monte Carlo Refinement of Disordered Silica Phases D.A. Keen. Modeling Single Crystal Diffuse Neutron Scattering Using Reverse Monte Carlo V.M. Nield. Real Space Rietveld: Full Profile Structural Refinement of the Atomic Pair Distribution Function S.J.L. Billinge. Advances in Pair Distribution Profile Fitting in Alloys M.F. Thorpe, et al. Local Atomic Arrangements in Binary Solid Solutions Studied by X-Ray and Neutron Diffuse Scattering from Single Crystals J.L. Robertson, et al. Fermi Surface Effects in the Diffuse Scattering from Alloys S.C. Moss, H. Reichert. Non-Mean-Field Theories of Short Range order and Diffuse Scattering Anomalies in Disordered Alloys I. Tsatskis. Diffuse Scattering by Crystals with Defects of Coulomb Displacement Field R.I. Barabash. 7 Additional Chapters. Index."
    },
    "137574965": {
      "title": "Diffuse Scattering and the Fundamental Properties of Materials",
      "abstract": "Diffuse Scattering - the use of off-specular X-Rays and neutrons from surfaces and interfaces - has grown rapidly as a tool for characterizing the surface properties of materials and related fundamental structural properties. It has proven to be especially useful in the understanding of local properties within materials. This new book reflects the efforts of physicists and materials scientists around the world who have helped to refine the techniques and applications of diffuse scattering. Major topics specifically covered include: Scattering in Low Dimensions; Elastic and Thermal Diffuse Scattering from Alloys; Scattering from Complex and Disordered Materials; and Scattering from Distorted Crystals."
    },
    "117125713": {
      "title": "Diffuse X-ray Scattering and Models of Disorder",
      "abstract": "Early theories of diffuse x-ray scattering from disordered crystals largely dealt with one-dimensional (1D) models and such concepts as 'correlation length' and 'domain size' are largely based on statistics of these 1D lattices. More recently, theories involving higher-dimensional models of disorder have evolved, and it is seen that the usefulness of some traditional concepts perhaps needs to be reappraised. The author reviews the earlier 1D models in order to develop the framework necessary for a discussion of the later higher-dimensional results. The theories are illustrated with optical analogue diffraction examples."
    }
  }
}